'''İbrahim Sirkeci''' (born 1972) is a [[British Turkish]] management scientist, Ria Financial Professor of Transnational Studies and Marketing at the [[European Business School London]], [[Regent's University London]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.regents.ac.uk/about/who-we-are/our-staff/ibrahim-sirkeci.aspx |title=Professor Ibrahim Sirkeci |publisher=Regents.ac.uk |accessdate=9 November 2014}}</ref> and Director of Regent's Centre for Transnational Studies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.regents.ac.uk/RCTS/ |title=Regent's Centre for Transnational Studies |publisher=Regents.ac.uk |accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref>

== Biography ==
Sirkeci received his BA in [[Political Science]] and [[Public Administration]] from [[Bilkent University]], [[Ankara]] and PhD in [[Human Geography]] from the [[University of Sheffield]].

Prior to joining the [[European Business School London]] of [[Regent's University London]], he worked as a Leverhulme Research Fellow at the Centre for the Study of Ethnicity and Citizenship, [[University of Bristol]],<ref>{{cite web| title =Bristol University: Sociology: Centre for Ethnicity & Citizenship: Members | publisher =University of Bristol| url =http://www.bristol.ac.uk/sociology/ethnicitycitizenship/urcmembers.html| accessdate =16 November 2007  }}</ref> and also as Assistant Professor at a private university in [[Ankara]], Turkey.

He is editor of several international [[peer-reviewed]] scholarly journals including ''[[Migration Letters]]'', ''[[Transnational Marketing Journal]]<ref>http://www.tplondon.com/journal/index.php/tmj/about/editorialTeam Transnational Marketing Journal Editorial Board</ref>'', and ''[[Goc Dergisi]]<ref>http://tplondon.com/dergi/index.php/gd/about/editorialTeam Goc Dergisi Editorial Board</ref>''. He authored several books including ''Cultures of [[Human migration|Migration]]'' published by [[University of Texas Press]] in 2011, and ''The Environment of Insecurity in Turkey and the Emigration of Turkish [[Kurds]] to Germany'', was published by [[Edwin Mellen Press]] in 2006.

== Work ==
Sirkeci's research focuses on human mobility, remittances, transnational marketing, marketing of higher education, transnational consumers, ethnicity, segmentation, segregation and labour markets,<ref name="socresonline1">[http://www.socresonline.org.uk/15/1/3.html The Impact of Spatial Segregation on the Employment Outcomes Amongst Bangladeshi Men and Women in England and Wales <!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> conflict, international migration with particular reference to minorities in the UK, [[Turkey|Turkish]], [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]] [[human migration|migration]] to Germany, Turkey and [[Iraq]].

He has written widely on transnational marketing,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.igi-global.com/Bookstore/TitleDetails.aspx?TitleId=487&DetailsType=Chapters |title=Segmentation challenges posed by Transnationals in mobile marketing |publisher=Igi-global.com |accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref> international migration, internal migration, population movements, labour market, segregation, ethnic conflict, minorities, Turks, Kurds, and remittances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metapress.com/content/h6501k416x2772kg/ |title=Remittances and the Global Financial Crisis |publisher=Metapress.com |date=4 October 2010 |accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref> Sirkeci also writes a weekly column for Turkish daily newspaper [[Birgun]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.birgun.net/writer_index.php?category_code=1220439751&news_code=1249819402&year=2009&month=08&day=09 |title=Freelonya'da Daltonlar Acilimi |publisher=Birgun.net |accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref> 
His research is published in journals including ''[[Environment and Planning A]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.envplan.com/abstract.cgi?id=a42180 |title=Ethno-religious categories and measuring occupational attainment in relation to education in England and Wales: a multilevel analysis |publisher=Envplan.com |accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref> ''[[Sociological Research Online]]'',<ref name="socresonline1"/> ''[[Ethnic and Racial Studies]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.informaworld.com/smpp/content~content=a713766349~db=all |title=The ethnic question in an environment of insecurity: the Kurds in Turkey |publisher=Informaworld.com |date=7 December 2010 |accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref> ''International Migration'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/bpl/imig/2001/00000039/00000004/art00003 |title=IngentaConnect Socio-economic Development and International Migration: A Turkish Study |publisher=Ingentaconnect.com |date=1 December 2001 |accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackwell-synergy.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1468-2435.2005.00338.x |title=Int Migration, Volume 43 Issue 4 Page 197-214, October 2005 (Article Abstract) |publisher=Blackwell Synergy |date=8 November 2005 |accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref> and ''[[Journal of Biosocial Science]]''.,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract?fromPage=online&aid=67795 |title=Cjo – Abstract – Variables That Explain Variation In Prenatal Care In Turkey; Social Class, Education And Ethnicity Re-Visited |publisher=Journals.cambridge.org |date=9 April 2001 |accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref> and Population Review<ref>{{cite web|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/login?uri=/journals/population_review/v043/43.1sirkeci.pdf |title=Project MUSE |publisher=Muse.jhu.edu |accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref>

